inn1.comm: not the best of starts, started wide and swung wider, a groan across the cold and dark United Kingdom and an easy decision for the umpire
better line, again a sniff of away swing
short of a length, on line, Vincent back and defends
leg side, thuds into the pads and a well-run single as the ball dribbles out into space
angled across Fleming and he was not remotely tempted by that one
again into the pads and another good, quick call from Vincent gets a second leg bye
short, flicked over square leg but not timed and long leg gets round to field 15 yards in from the rope
short on leg stump, turned round the corner quite easily
good ball, it bounced as well, and Vincent let it pass inches outside off stump
slightly fuller, found the edge of Vincent's bat, along the ground but it was a no-ball anyway despite the chorus of noise from behind the stumps
a wide to follow the no-ball, down the leg and Vincent didn't have to move as it sneaked behind him
fuller and straighter, blocked with hard hands to mid-on
same line, check-block to cover where Dalrymple half stops - he should have done better than that - and allows the one
on leg stump, sweetly flicked round the corner, never a chance of long leg, who is too wide, to even think about stopping that
outside off stump,Fleming leaves that
thuds into the pads and after two quick leg-byes in the last over, the fielders are slightly closer and swoop
a wide called but a bit harsh. If the umpires are consistent we might be here all day if they call all of those ...
jags back into Vincent and hits him high on the pad, no appeal
leg stump, clipped through midwicket all along the ground, lovely control and it just has enough legs to creep over the rope
a foot outside off stump and Vincent shoulders arms
another wide, less doubt about that one as it sailed towards first slip
Plunkett overcorrects and Vincent flicks him down to long leg
a rather ungainly defensive prod on the walk into the leg side
prodded into the ground, the ball bounces at his feet and drops just behind the stumps
Vincent onto the back foot again to defend. Better bowling to start his second over from Tremlett ...
same length - slightly short - outside off stump and left
but that's is clearly a wide - the fifth so far
slightly straighter, still wide enough to leave, but the in-house close cordon react as if it was the ball of the century
not quite yorker-length but Vincent has to hurry to dig that out
cuts back in, strikes Vincent, who was up on his toes, high on the front foot, a loud appeal but only from Tremlett as that was going well over the top
short, disdainfully swatted over square leg
and once more too short, pulled this time through midwicket
fuller, Fleming drawn forward to defensively drive, much better
and again Fleming pulled forward to block
swings wide down the leg side, Fleming shapes to flick it away but it's too wide for him to do that
slanted across Fleming who momentarily looks as if he is going to chase it but he doesn't

full and swinging in, Fleming caught in no-man's land and it raps him on the pad  but looks for all the world to have got a thin inside edge to that. If he didn't then it was plumb ... the umpire has no doubts
turned to long leg
Fulton can do no more than push into the off side
good length, Fulton blocks to mid-on
short out side off stump, Fulton leaves alone
good line, again Fulton leaves, and the incessant chirping in overdrive after three decent balls
tip and run to mid-on, Fulton took the pace off that and called immediately, never a sniff of danger
good length on off stump, Fulton back and into line
Fulton drawn forward and he misses an airy drive

Rubbish! Short and wide, hammered to short coverby Fulton and Bell makes a great stop ... and then hurls the ball at the non-striker's end where Flintoff is slow to back up and it's overthrows. Utterly unnecessary and that is simply bad cricket
down the leg side, a wide had it not tickled Fulton's pads as it passed
push and run to mid-on where Flintoff is slow to react ... boy, does he look stiff as he fields that!
short and Fulton leaves it
turned into space between midwicket and mid-on
too full, flicked round the corner to long leg
short, worked round behind square on the leg, but the pace was off that and the pair ran well as Panesar thundered in and unleashed a powerful throw
Vincent forced back to block
far too short and a no-ball as well, Vincent not quite onto that and it trundles to Panesar at long leg
dropped into the leg side but midwicket quickly in to scotch thoughts of a run
again down the leg, clipped fine and Panesar does well to keep them to one
firm defensive prod, edged into the front pad and momentarily Plunkett thought he might get a return catch, but it dropped well short
poor line, so easy for Fulton to shimmy inside the ball and run it fine on the leg side
Fulton back and across, good response from Plunkett

dropped ... Fulton looks to work that through midwicket but gets an uncontrolled leading edge which loops high over the bowler's head and Flintoff runs back from mid-on, in semi slow motion, and makes a despairing dive a yard outside the fielding circle but doesn't get a hand to it.  Harsh, possibly, but others would have
full and on off stump, Fulton looks to drive, gets a thin edge and Nixon does well to take a low catch tumbling to his right
turned to long leg, good fielding by Tremlett prevents a second
down the leg side
Taylor gropes as the ball beats him outside off stump
pushed to extra cover and a good, quick single
full, Vincent back and across to defend into the leg side
almost a wide outside off stump but he got away with that one
six inches closer to off stump and Vincent leaves it alone
and another leg-side wide ... simply not good enough says Ian Botham for the 403rd time this series, and for once the BBB team agrees
flicked off the pads into the leg side
lovely ball, right line, right length and Vincent left sparring at air
pushed to cover and another easy run
pushed to mid-on
very wide and chased by Taylor, he had no need to play at that and really had to reach to miss it
worked into space through midwicket, poor ball well played
Vincent throws the bat at another widish one and the ball flashes six inches over the one-handed leap of first slip. Had he missed, it would have been a wide
super ball first up, 86mph (138kph) and it races through Taylor
down the leg and flicked fine by Taylor, and Flintoff's pace does the rest
dropped down towards square leg, but with the pace taken off the ball it was a good, well-run single.  With good calling and a decent understanding between batsmen, there are runs almost everywhere
outside off, shortish and the batsman not tempted
prodded into the off side and the fielders converge
much the same, but this time left alone
good start, Taylor prods and misses
that one ripped past the bat, some real turn there
wide, Taylor steps back and swats it through extra cover
good line, blocked
short and wide, smacked through the covers
short, Vincent back to cut and misses
Taylor right into line to block a ball right on the button
worked to leg in a very ungainly fashion, off balance, and short midwicket in very quickly
again Dalrymple in very quickly from shortish midwicket ... "that's magic JD," chirps Nixon
banged in but on this pitch that's meat and drink, Taylor onto it very quickly and he hammers it over midwicket. JD's role this time is retrieval.
short and that jarred Taylor's bottom hand
Taylor beaten this time as he shaped to flick to leg, a loud appeal but it was probably going over the leg stump
Vincent right forward to defend
Vincent aims a swish and the ball trickles off the pads to slip
punched off the back foot past short extra cover
ripper which turns and Vincent leaves
again too short, Vincent waits and hammers it through extra cover and it's beautifully timed and placed and beats the man on the rope
watchfully defended
Flintoff on the spot
full and quite lovely placement off his toes by Taylor between midwicket and mid-on
Taylor closes the face and works that square on the leg side from off stump, into space and they get two even though the ball was within a few yards of fielders
wide, Taylor looks to hit the cover off it and misses by some way
Taylor forced back and he can do no more than push it back to the bowler
steered to Collingwood at backward point, he stops well and then hurls the ball at the non-striker's end
"Let's mix it hear Monts," says Nixon as Panesar starts with it on the spot
cut to point where Collingwood stops well
blocked ... Panesar has found a groove here
Vincent looks to cut but is undone by extra bounce
again Vincent can only defend
pushed forward,bat-pad into the off side
loose drive, thick edge into space and down to third man
tip and run to point, quick call, Strauss races in, picks up, and dives as he underarms at the stumps from three yards  ... he hits but the batsman is easily home
slower ball out the back of the hand, turned to leg
flicked behind square leg, Joyce fields well to prevent the second
dead batted into the covers, another quick run and Vincent would have beaten Collingwood's throw at the non-striker's end even had he hit

turned round the corner to Panesar, who is up saving the one, and he juggles and then throws down the stumps at the striker's end ... never remotely close to a run-out but the crowd cheers as if it was
too full, driven straight on the leg side and it beats the despairing dive of Plunkett at mid-on
better, blocked
wide and left alone
Taylor, as he so often does, tries to work that into the leg side but this time he fails
pushed to mid-on
and once more Taylor can only prod toward mid-on. "TRhat's what we want, Monts, that's what we want," opines Nixon
slightly too short, swatted from off stump over mid-on for four
slower ball completely bamboozles Vincent, it hits him high and the pad and a loud appeal is turned down. Too high by some way
only just too short and Vincent onto his front foot slams it back past Flintoff ... much as Federer would hit a forehand down the line
dropped ... hit hard on the up and Bell fails to hold on to a stinger at short cover
left alone outside off stump
shorter but again he's not tempted
straight and blocked with real caution
fired through outside off stump and left
wider and again left
a wry smile as Taylor mistimes an attempted flick ... almost a leading edge
beats the outside edge and Nixon whips the bails off ... Steve Davis not interested and Nixon then suggests he calls for the third umpire
turns past the outside edge
reverse sweep, well stopped and Taylor has to dive for safely at the bowler's end
flicked into the leg side
spun down the leg side
short and hit with real venom square on the leg side
played into the leg side with the spin ... off the thigh pad
worked behind square on the leg
and again turned behind square on the leg
Pushed into the covers, Taylor looks for one but Vincent having none of it
started wide, got wider
driven firmly back to Panesar who fields well
spins quite some way and left alone
this time Vincent wants the single but Taylor sends him back
driven to mid-on, a quick call and Plunkett rather leaden footed
Taylor leaves that ... another good over from Panesar
good line and length to start, defended circumspectly
turned fine on the leg and Panesar makes a good diving stop just inside the ropes ...massive cheer from a sparse crowd
driven to extra cover
beats Taylor, a loud appeal but a hint of an inside edge and the ball squirts into the off side
driven hard through extra cover and a call of "two" before the ball is even off the square
pulled unconvincingly past short midwicket, it was out of reach despite the chorus of "catch it" from all and sundry
turned round to long leg
attempted reverse sweep but the ball sailed down the leg side
flicked fine down the leg side ...this happens too often and it's easy runs
swatted through midwicket off one knee
and again, hit harder this time but straight to Strauss on the deep midwicket rope
leg side again, flicked very fine
turned square on the leg side
left alone inches outside the off stump
punched into the off side
worked round to long leg
driven up to long-on with a yell of "two". They amble one
dropped no more than eight yards into the leg side but an easy run nevertheless as Nixon has to scurry out to field
steered into the leg side, sweetly placed between long leg and deep square leg and they run an easy two
neatly flicked into space in the midwicket area
big turn deceives the batsman, loud appeal from Nixon but not really for anything
driven to extra cover, a loud cheer as some thought it was a catch
worked round the corner
slightly cross-batted drive  to deepish mid-on
off the pads down the leg side and Nixon makes a good tumbling, scurrying, scrambling stop
driven straight back to Collingwood
angled behind square on the off
hit high and straight but more nine iron than three, and it is stopped inside the rope by long-on coming round
very neat flick, he waits and then just feathers the ball through where slips would be to bring up his fifty
driven hard and Bell makes a good diving stop at short extra cover
defensive push into the off side
spun down the leg side, yet another wide
flicked with the spin on the leg side
another one spins past the batsman on the leg side and Nixon, semi avoiding a big swish, misses it as well
flicked to long leg
better line but another single as Taylor drops and run to bring up his second one-day fifty
textbook reverse sweep (if there is such a thing) past the man on the 45 on the off
down the leg side ... the umpire must have thought that flicked the batsman
pushed into the off side
left alone
a big heave, an inside edge and the ball ends up trundling down to long leg
short and pulled off the toe of the bat to deep midwicket
driven uppishly through the covers to the man in the deep
stroked to long-on
Taylor waits and turns that to deepish midwicket
defended quietly
defended once more, off the back foot into midwicket
just down the leg-side and that's England's 14th wide. Well bowled
squeezed out to mid-on and the batsmen set off immediately for a quick single
leg-side line and the batsman helps it round to fine for a jogged run
doesn't quite get hold of that one - an attempted pull to midwicket - the ball crashes down and the batsman rehearses the shot with a few fresh-air swishes
"Hoooooow?" begin the fielders as that one pitches on middle and raps the batsman on the pad. Not a bad shout, but HawkEye has it missing leg, just, and slightly too high
defended off the back foot into the covers and the fielder rushes in quickly over that one
takes the ball from off-stump and caresses it to mid-on
ooh, expansive waft, hoping to launch that one to square, but the ball pitches wide, an attempted legcutter, and bends wider - and the batsman completely misses it
doesn't connect cleanly once more, slapping that down into the ground and it balloons up to midwicket
another slash at one he's trying to work from outside off to the leg-side and it doesn't come off again
gets a run this time, but on the off-side, driving it tidily out to the covers without much power
worked off the backfoot into the midwicket

good effort in the deep from Strauss, going for the catch off the flick to square, it bounces just before him but he gets his body behind it and cuts off three runs. Something for his coach to smile about
worked off the legs for two this time
straight, and the ball pops up at him unexpectedly, so he stuns it off the back foot
walks backward to give himself room on the off-side to lace that through the off-side
drops that one short and Taylor's quickly onto it, on the front foot and swatting it like a tennis shot through midwicket
waits for that one and dinks it off the back foot to cover
smashed away on the on-side and that's carried in front of midwicket for a flat six. Top shot!

good bowling from Collingwood, the slower ball, a legcutter and Taylor sails that up to long-on (his hand coming off the bat) where it's Panesar... and can he... oh, Monty makes that catch look easy! Ah, it was. Nevermind, he's cool in collecting it and cool in celebrating - pointing a finger up in the air, as if to say who da man
Vincent has strike as they crossed and he works out to the leg-sdie where Panesar calmly collects one more
played off the back foot
ooh, look at that swing away from the righthander... but that's "Wide" as announced stoutly by the umpire
left alone
movement off the pitch there, and a hint of swing, too; good ball
played safely and softly off the back foot into the covers and will they run? "No"
swing again, but short of a good length and the batsman works it calmly off his back foot
great shot! Early decision to come down the pitch, Tremlett can't change his length in time, and that's stroked away straight through mid-on. Lovely!
good comeback from Tremlett, in that hallway of hesitancy just outside off, but the batsman decides to leave it
on leg and that's worked away off the legs fine and the single brings up New Zealand's 200. Good batting from the Kiwis so far
tasty stuff first up - the batsman hits the ball back to Flintoff who mock-shies at his stumps and that stirs the crowd a touch
worked off the legs in front of midwicket
yorker, well bowled
slower ball this time - good ideas from Flintoff, mixing it up
saw the batsman backing away to give himself room and Flintoff follows him, pinging the ball in at his toes
on leg this time, less deliberately, and that's worked off the pads - literally - fine
worked off the back foot to point
defended tidily
bends that across the righthander, who slashes and connects only with air. Nixon pouches the ball
slinks invitingly across the righthander who, feet rooted in the crease, slashes and misses
defended again
ah. Got the edge but there's no slip and that dribbles away. Good bowling from Panesar, applying the pressure and eventually frustrating the batsman into such a shot
slower ball, gets the outside edge and that runs fine - again there's no slip - and that's consecutive boundaries
pushed right up there, well bowled, and that's defended solidly
good cricket. The batsman pushes to mid-on, Flintoff dives and gets a hand, while the batsmen take a well-judged quick single
pitches on off, that's worked off the back foot to the covers but a big roar of a "No!" quashes thoughts of the single
pushed right up there again, but the batsman manages to squeeze out a single to mid-off to rotate the strike once more. Good stuff from New Zealand
great yorker to finish, dug out to short midwicket
on a good length, that's nibbled into short midwicket and the batsmen rush through - good running
beats the outside edge again - Panesar has bowled well this match

gone this time! Tidy work from Nixon and Panesar gets the wicket he deserves, McMillan down the track to get after Panesar and misses completely. Panesar sets off in his endearingly lost-in-his-own-world celebrations, skipping and whirring his finger around
good throw in from short in on the leg-side
worked into the leg-side
defended
defended first up and that's "Well bowled, Fred. Come on Fred"
outside off, worked into the covers and that's "A good line, Fred", Nixon kindly commentating for us
dabbed down off the back foot to gully where there's a great pick-up-and-throw from the knees, just failing to take the non-striker's stumps. A direct hit would have been close
Oram off the mark with a dink into the covers
sleek single into the covers
leg-side wide, just
worked off the back foot down to Tremlett, fittingly at long leg, and he spears it back into Nixon who takes the ball neatly over his head and looks for a run out, which isn't on
and the change does the trick! An easy chip to midwicket, dolly catching practice for Dalrymple, really, short in on the legs. Smart captaincy from Flintoff
worked round to fine and there's two quick runs there for New Zealand. Well run
chased that down leg, but it was a tad wide
nibbled off the legs, but misses out on a juicy one, thinks about running but Oram barks, "No!"
"Waiting, waiting!" they decide as that's worked into the covers off the back foot
"Yes!" this time, tucked off the hips into the leg-side and the batsmen decide on two to Strauss's arms. More good running from them
gloved, but short of Nixon. Extra bounce for Plunkett ... and an extra run for New Zealand to their total
worked off the back foot into gully
left alone outside off
swept round in front of square
worked to midwicket for a single

great sweep, poor fielding. Tremlett stiff in the outfield and "That's rubbish" says Martin. "It comes to something when Panesar's not amused with the fielding. Actually, he's fielded very well today."
single into the leg-side
played forward with a defensive shot to please textbook makers, coaches and sponsors alike
worked round behind square
down leg for yet another wide - that's 20 this innings so far
got away with that one - could have been a wide on the off-side, but it was just inside the lines. Nevertheless, the lefthander chose to leave it
rushes that round fine and Panesar does well to slide and retrieve in a smooth action
cut away off the back foot, straight to a fielder
straight, a touch short, but takes the power off a cut
well bowled. That's close, bending back in at the lefthander but he just got outside the line - good decision
nice! Down on one knee and slog-sweeps that in front of midwicket with enough meat on it to open a (Mark) butcher's shop. Shot!

good reply. Change of pace, flighting that in just outside off and it moves ever so slightly away from the righthander, almost caressing the edge. Entertaining cricket, this - good batting and bowling, as we like it
waiting this time, just defending that
slog-sweep again but doesn't quite get hold of it and that finds the fielder

"Catch, catch, catch!" suggests Nixon and Strauss obliges, taking that running forward and carrying on a few steps with the momentum. McCullum was going leg-side, it was too wide, so he had to adjust on the off-side. Good cameo nevertheless
short, worked to gully and thrown back in sharply. Nixon growls his appreciation, with a big "Grrrrrrrr!"
worked to mid-off
driven to a straight long-on, quick shuffling from the batsmen
ooh, that flew off the top of the bat, squared up and the batsman starts to walk off, but he just chipped Dalrymple, and has to rush tomake his ground
worked out in front of midwicket
high and veering down leg. Oh dear
driven straight and high but that lands in space just inside the boundary
full toss, help yourself. The batsman doesn't take full advantage though, just working that away off his legs
on leg again, and the batsman comes forward to make that a half-volley off his toes
uses his feet and drives that straight down the ground and it's pouched by a man in the crowd who's really pleased with himself. As well he might be
worked into the legs
waits for it, and dinks it forward
pushed into the leg-side
wide down off and a strongly hit cover drive results in just a single, as it's straight to the fielder
dug out from the off-side for a quick single to mid-on
wide again and that's sent aerial into space in the extra-cover region. No-ball for overstepping makes New Zealand's score even healthier
length ball and tries to clear mid-off, but Plunkett at long-off, running backwards, holds on for a relatively easy catch
worked out off the back foot for an easy single
worked off the legs for an easy single in front of square
played off the back foot down in front of him
wide and slapped away square of the wicket on the off
wide again outside off and that's worked out to the man at deep cover who wings it back in flat
squirted to leg and the batsmen take on a risky two, Vettori turning blind to boot - but the return throw's too high for Nixon to deal with in tim
well placed on the off-side, what a fantastic shot. Flintoff moved an extra man on the off-side, so Vettori stepped across his stumps and went leg-side
worked out to off
worked into the covers this time
played off the back foot and that's village from Plunkett at long-off, just letting the ball trickle through his fingers. Flintoff's hands on hips, unamused
smashed for a huge six in front of midwicket! Rubbing salt into the wound there, all right. And a bit of pepper. Possibly some vinegar
what a shot! Straight drive over long-off and that's a beautiful crack, cleanly struck
low full toss, slashes at it with big shoulders, gets a low edge which dribbles away and that's the 300 up!
worked to long-on this time
taken from middle stump and worked round to the man on the 45
quick single brings Oram on strike
wide, Oram flashes at that, just fails to get an upper-edge. That's called wide which is probably a bit harsh, bouncing as it did in the tramlines
lovely shot! This is such a good innings by Oram, this time digging out a ball that's nearly a yorker, and driving it straight again
wide down off, Oram tries to lay bat on that, but is too late on the shot and Nixon pouches
late cut down to third man and that's a poor throw from Tremlett, wild and well, rubbish
one-bounce four from a low full toss to bring his fifth one-day fifty, this one coming from just 32 balls
an aerial slash in front of midwicket lands comfortably inside the rope

inn2.comm: gets an inside edge immediately, well bowled, squaring up Joyce... the ball runs away outside second slip
defended forward
nicely timed off the legs to midwicket
on the money, the left armer delivering that one across the righthander, who defends
defended squarely, walking forward into the shot and the batsmen decide not to take on a run
prodded defensively into the off and again the decision is "Waiting, waiting"
worked into the covers
worked down to the third-man boundary
left alone outside off
ooh, great ball, left alone and that one cuts right back in at him and just to say bounces over the stumps
what a great shot, down on one knee and that's sent cleanly into the (sadly empty) stands
defensive shot to end the over
worked to square, straight to the fielder
straight and the batsman bends over it in defence
good ball, that, beating the outside edge and it's pouched tidily by the keeper
left alone outside off; that one sails harmlessly through
speared in just in front of off and that's defended down
outside off, short, but Joyce misses out
left alone outside off
close call. Bond using the inswinger well, angling in late, and HawkEye - as well as our naked eyes - had that clattering into leg stump. The umpire was unmoved, though, and it's his eyes that count
worked to cover this time
tickled off the legs but straight to the fielder at square
driven to mid-on
nicely timed through cover, just stroked it away for four, and it eases to the rope
across the righthander and that one's worked into the covers
short and cleanly pummelled away through midwicket
big appeal for one which appeared to have shaved the outside edge, but the keeper and slips stayed down, tellingly, and replays showed it was bat hitting pad
swept finely and that goes all the way, fast
straight and that's defended forward
swings away from the righthander, but enough for him to leave that one alone
good response from Franklin and gets the edge this time, snapped tidily at first slip. Loye was tempted to drive that and he's a victim of the angle across him once more
defends off the back foot strongly first up and there's a loud call of "No!"
straight, and that's worked down to cover off the back foot with nothing more than a defensive push
defended this time
short and Joyce swivels to pull that behind square; he doesn't quite time it and it's whipped back in sharply
nice ball that, on a good length and darting a touch back in at the righthander off the seam - but he does well to judge the leave
worked off the back foot into covers and the batsmen wait ... and decide not to risk the single
defended off the back foot
takes the pace off it a tad, but that's worked to mid-on, and there's a quick single. Well done, everyone
worked behind point and they wait
driven to mid-off
decides if he's going to slash, which he does, it had better be hard, and it is - that one flying over the slips and if they'd have had a fly catcher in that one would've been gone
worked well off the back foot down to third man and he stealks the strike
defended this time
driven to cover
worked into the off-side
slower ball and that's defended to the gully
tickled out to mid-on
driven straight to mid-off and without much power
defended down
punched off the back foot into midwicket, poorly timed
quick running there
played down off the back foot
straight down to third man
defended into the covers and will they risk a single? "No!"
defended down off the back foot into the covers
ah, died on Vincent in the covers there - looked at first to be a chance as that was slammed down off the back foot, reaching out for that one
dances down and helps that from outside off over to midwicket
swivelled round to midwicket
short and wide and swatted off the back foot, cut through point. That's laced away
straight, and the batsman defends over the ball
worked to midwicket
short, a touch of width and the batsman squeezes out that to point
helped over to midwicket
driven to cover
defended down off the back foot
straight and defended down
works off the back foot and that's helped out over cover
a touch of width outside off and that's worked down off the back foot
worked into short midwicket
just helped that into gully
driven straight to the man at cover
now that's a nice shot, leg stump, and sweetly struck in front of midwicket
defended down
driven straight, clean hit, and that's laced away
dinked down and there's some quick running
dabbed down off the back foot
worked down through gully
worked off the back foot straight to the man at cover
short and worked down to third man for a quick single
tries to work that through cover, completely misses it and that bobbles off the keeper's gloves
somehow finds the gap in a packed off-side ring - a bit of luck for him there, as an outside leading edge pops up off the slower ball
whipped away in front of midwicket
dabbed down to just inside the third man boundary
worked towards mid-on and shelled by the bowler - hard chance
Bell living dangerously here - clangs that one off the toe-end of the bat wide of mid-on
chased that down leg
backs away to make room and lamps that through cover
worked into short midwicket
drags a slower ball down a touch short and that's laced through cover
on leg and that's defended forward
driven straight to mid-off
worked round off the legs, tickled very fine and that's a good shot
thought about the second run after guiding that down to third man
bends that across the righthander who dinks it down to gully off the back foot and it's "Waiting, no"
defended down
driven straight through mid-off, a nice shot
defended down this time
swept behind square
laced behind point but that's picked up
worked in front of midwicket
caressed to midwicket
timed to square
good length outside off stump. Defended off the back foot and picked up in the covers

pushed into the covers

watchful start
quicker ball fizzes through as Strauss shoulders arms
shorter and an attempted carve. Missed
a bit of width, left alone

width, and a hint of turn. Left alone again
edge, but beats everything! Keeper, slip, and everything else. A let-off, but more juicy turn for Patel

looking for the sweep, but misses

quicker and fuller, defended staunchly
good start, off on stump, tweaking towards leg
nudged to leg as Strauss walks across his stumps
still aiming for the gaps on the leg-side, but not finding them on this occasion. Good bowling

down on the sweep, finds the gap
shovelled into the leg-side to complete a tidy over

fuller length, played out to point

nurdled into the leg-side
picks that gap again

played out to the deep, and another single

defended, and McCullum tidies up
played off the back foot, finds that gap in the covers again

good length again from Patel, cut to point to complete the over

bit of a mix-up between the new batsmen, but they get away with it. Jitters from England
clipped square, another single
round the wicket, and nudged off the pads, can't beat short fine leg
good flight again, no way through

firm push-drive through the covers. Nice elegant shot, and good running too

worked into the covers

drawn forward, and solid defence
on the front foot again, and defended with an angled bat into the leg-side

worked into the leg-side

short and bursts past the bat
defended again

excellent over. No freebies whatsoever

nice bowling again - big shout for lbw, but Flintoff is outside the line

good line and length, but nudged for a single. Just a gentle offcutter
solid length delivery. Defended off the back foot
short, and dabbed to third man

beaten. Well bowled

twirled onto that tricky length, defended
slightly leg-sided, and defended into the gap
defended again. Lovely tight and varied stuff

no singles to be had, let alone boundaries at the moment
brilliant bowling. Ball-on-a-string stuff
another off-cutter, but slightly off target. Drilled into the deep, but swept up on the boundary
quicker and straighter, defended off the back foot
pushed into the leg-side, still no way through

tight on off stump. Defended again
drawn forward, and steered into the covers

a squeak of approval as this one beats the bat
down the track and chipped over midwicket to get off the mark

good length, defended ... once again ... off the back foot
fuller, and driven. McMillan fields with an exaggerated tumble

twirled onto a length
outside off again. Dalrymple steps across and makes a hash of his nothing of a shot
worked into the leg-side. This match is officially dying on its feet
a big swish and a miss

worked to point this time. It's as flat as England's Ashes-victory champagne

driven for one more. And the run-rate continues to rise
down on one knee. A missed sweep

short and cutting in a fraction. Defended off the back foot
worked into the covers

slapped into the deep, to keep the strike
